<div class="col-md-12">
    <h2><u>How Organisations should help prevent Attacks.</u></h2>
    <p> Knowing how to prevent these attacks can help stop you falling prey to some of them at home or at work like a phishing attack however your employer or organisation also has a duty to train and inform their employee's of some of the dangers. </p>
    <dl>
        <dd>- Companies should have some kind of awareness and Cybersecurity training programme. Ensure that you take it and absorb the knowledge and if they do not then request one. (They will thank you later.)</dd>
        <dd>- Installing and regularly updating anti-phishing and anti-spam filters for emails is a must. Office 365 offer a service for this.</dd>
    </dl>
    <p>Most of these attacks come through email to help prevent this companies should have Domain-Based Message authentication reporting and conformance (DMARC) rules. It consists of two technologies these are called Sender Policy Framework (SPF) and Domain Keys Identified Mail (DKIM). "SPF is a DNS-based filtering control that helps to identify spoofed messages and DKIM involves the use of an encrypted signature to verify the sender’s identity. That signature is created using the organization’s public key and is decrypted using the private key available to the email server." (An Easy Way to Block Email Impersonation Attacks on Businesses - SpamTitan, 2019) </p>


